01:07:27.790 --> 01:07:29.610
-Hi, I'm Traci Abbott.

01:07:29.610 --> 01:07:32.740
I'm a professor of English
and Media Studies and Gender

01:07:32.740 --> 01:07:34.930
Studies program at
Bentley University.

01:07:38.880 --> 01:07:42.250
We've been talking about a
fixing prefixes to identities

01:07:42.250 --> 01:07:44.340
and communities, and
how you feel about it

01:07:44.340 --> 01:07:45.740
being a fix to movements?

01:07:45.740 --> 01:07:49.380
Because as someone who's
worked with genderqueer

01:07:49.380 --> 01:07:51.520
and transgender representations
for a long time,

01:07:51.520 --> 01:07:54.340
a recent collection came
out about transfeminisms

01:07:54.340 --> 01:07:55.380
by Anne Enke.

01:07:55.380 --> 01:07:57.880
And it was very helpful
for me, personally,

01:07:57.880 --> 01:07:59.830
because it bridged this
divide between queer

01:07:59.830 --> 01:08:02.660
studies and feminist studies.

01:08:02.660 --> 01:08:06.720
And it of course, engaged in the
conversations about feminisms.

01:08:06.720 --> 01:08:09.950
But at the same time, calling
it transfeminism somehow

01:08:09.950 --> 01:08:12.460
also makes it seem
distinct from feminism,

01:08:12.460 --> 01:08:15.700
which to me is about gender
equality for all genders,

01:08:15.700 --> 01:08:18.630
not just two genders or
people with a gender.

01:08:18.630 --> 01:08:21.130
So I'm curious about
how you see prefixes

01:08:21.130 --> 01:08:25.700
like that when they're fixed
to movements or disciplines

01:08:25.700 --> 01:08:28.420
as being useful,
because they're infusing

01:08:28.420 --> 01:08:31.359
a perspective into the
traditional definition that

01:08:31.359 --> 01:08:34.210
makes it broader, but at
the same time maintaining

01:08:34.210 --> 01:08:37.800
a binary between, say,
transfeminism and feminism,

01:08:37.800 --> 01:08:39.390
as if it's a false binary.

01:08:39.390 --> 01:08:41.700
Like they're not
on the same thing.

01:08:41.700 --> 01:08:43.200
-I think it [INAUDIBLE]
be important

01:08:43.200 --> 01:08:48.100
for us to be exacting in our
language about what our work

01:08:48.100 --> 01:08:49.550
is, and what it centers.

01:08:49.550 --> 01:08:51.250
So I would assume
in transfeminism,

01:08:51.250 --> 01:08:54.410
the work centers trans
folk within the fight

01:08:54.410 --> 01:08:58.090
for gender equity.

01:08:58.090 --> 01:09:02.850
I think that if we think about
the definition of who created

01:09:02.850 --> 01:09:06.550
and what feminism is, it often
didn't include women of color,

01:09:06.550 --> 01:09:08.560
for example, or poor women.

01:09:08.560 --> 01:09:11.370
And so it took a
lot of poor women,

01:09:11.370 --> 01:09:14.920
specifically I think about
black women, like Barbara Smith,

01:09:14.920 --> 01:09:17.899
to say, we're going to
have black feminism.

01:09:17.899 --> 01:09:21.540
And so I think that it's OK to
have those separate spaces that

01:09:21.540 --> 01:09:35.000
are part of this larger umbrella
of what the original term is.

01:09:35.000 --> 01:09:36.439
I guess I'm not
bothered by people

01:09:36.439 --> 01:09:40.510
creating their own within.

01:09:40.510 --> 01:09:42.370
-Well, what I'm
hoping though, too,

01:09:42.370 --> 01:09:45.340
is that if it does undermine
the concept of say,

01:09:45.340 --> 01:09:47.540
feminism being only for
certain kinds of women.

01:09:47.540 --> 01:09:49.760
Certain kinds of privileged
women in particular.

01:09:49.760 --> 01:09:50.356
-But it does.

01:09:50.356 --> 01:09:51.439
A part of it does, though.

01:09:51.439 --> 01:09:51.850
-Right.

01:09:51.850 --> 01:09:52.683
-That's the reality.

01:09:52.683 --> 01:09:56.130
And so I think that it probably
was created in reaction

01:09:56.130 --> 01:09:58.710
to being in probably such
a space that was just

01:09:58.710 --> 01:10:02.710
seen as feminism, that didn't
want these people a part of it.

01:10:02.710 --> 01:10:05.980
And so the radical,
revolutionary, resistant thing

01:10:05.980 --> 01:10:09.000
is then to go and say that,
we are still a part of this,

01:10:09.000 --> 01:10:10.945
and we'll still fight
for your liberation,

01:10:10.945 --> 01:10:13.010
but because you're
not fighting for ours,

01:10:13.010 --> 01:10:16.810
we need to create a space where
our liberation is centered.

01:10:16.810 --> 01:10:19.320
And so I think that that's
what it probably came from,

01:10:19.320 --> 01:10:24.640
because if feminism was
really for everybody, then

01:10:24.640 --> 01:10:27.300
we wouldn't have
these other spaces.

01:10:27.300 --> 01:10:29.520
-Thank you.

